            <entry xml:id="entry_kʼala_2" n="2" xml:lang="os-x-iron">
                <form type="lemma"><orth>kʼala</orth></form>
                <usg><lang/></usg>
                <sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                        <q>олово</q>
                    </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                        <q>tin</q>
                    </abv:tr></sense>
                <etym xml:lang="ru">Из <mentioned xml:lang="ar" extralang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>qalʽī</w>
                        <gloss><q>олово</q></gloss></mentioned>; вероятно, через грузинское
                    посредство: <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/>
                        <w>k’ala</w>
                        <gloss><q>олово</q></gloss></mentioned>. Вошло во многие языки Кавказа:
                        <mentioned xml:lang="sva"><lang/>
                        <w>k’ala</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="bbl"><lang/>
                        <w>k’al</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="dar"><lang/>
                        <w>q’alaj</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="lez"><lang/>
                        <w>k’ele</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="lbe"><lang/>
                        <w>qalaj</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ce"><lang/>
                        <w>ghali</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ady"><lang/>
                        <w>galai</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ab"><lang/>
                        <w>a-k’alej</w></mentioned> и др. С давних пор свидетельствуется на
                    %bтюркской%b почве: куман. и др. <mentioned xml:lang="trk"><lang/>
                        <w>qālāi</w>
                        <gloss><q>олово</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Радлов"/><biblScope>II 226</biblScope></bibl>). Сюда же
                        <mentioned xml:lang="gr"><lang/>
                        <w>καλάι</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sr"><lang/>
                        <w>kalaj</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="bg"><lang/>
                        <w>кaлaй</w></mentioned>. Первоисточником считается название города
                    %iQualah%i на Малакке, где с давних пор в большом количестве добывалось олово
                            (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Schrader"/><biblScope>II
                            701</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><author>V.
                            %sМinоrskу%s</author><biblScope xml:lang="ru">Hudud al ’Alam. 1937, стр.
                            187</biblScope></bibl>).%n<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._ОЭ"/><biblScope>III 12</biblScope></bibl>;
                            <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."
                            /><biblScope>8</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Hübschmann._Arm._Gr."/><biblScope>269</biblScope></bibl>.—
                            <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>52,
                            519</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
                <etym xml:lang="en">From <mentioned xml:lang="ar" extralang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>qalʽī</w>
                        <gloss><q>tin</q></gloss></mentioned>; probably, through Georgian:
                        <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/>
                        <w>k’ala</w>
                        <gloss><q>tin</q></gloss></mentioned>. It entered many Caucasian languages:
                        <mentioned xml:lang="sva"><lang/>
                        <w>k’ala</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="bbl"><lang/>
                        <w>k’al</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="dar"><lang/>
                        <w>q’alaj</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="lez"><lang/>
                        <w>k’ele</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="lbe"><lang/>
                        <w>qalaj</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ce"><lang/>
                        <w>ghali</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ady"><lang/>
                        <w>galai</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ab"><lang/>
                        <w>a-k’alej</w></mentioned> etc. Frow way back it is attested in %bTurkic%b
                    languages: Cuman etc. <mentioned xml:lang="trk"><lang/>
                        <w>qālāi</w>
                        <gloss><q>tin</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Радлов"/><biblScope>II 226</biblScope></bibl>). See also
                        <mentioned xml:lang="el"><lang/>
                        <w>καλάι</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sr"><lang/>
                        <w>kalaj</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="bg"><lang/>
                        <w>kalaj</w></mentioned>. The primary source is considered to be the name of
                    %iQualah%i city at the Malay Peninsula, where tin has been extracted in large
                    quantities for a long time (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Schrader"
                            /><biblScope>II 701</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><author>V.
                            %sМinоrskу%s</author><biblScope xml:lang="en">Hudud al ’Alam. 1937, p.
                            187</biblScope></bibl>).%n<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._ОЭ"/><biblScope>III 12</biblScope></bibl>;
                            <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."
                            /><biblScope>8</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Hübschmann._Arm._Gr."/><biblScope>269</biblScope></bibl>.—
                            <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>52,
                            519</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
            </entry>
